{"/service/ndnp/dlc/batch_dlc_noone_ver01/data/sn83045462/00280600696/1930052501/0672.xml":{"full_text":"News of Markets\nPaget 1 to 4\nPart 6\u201412 Paget\nBRANCH AND GROUP\nBANKS BIG ISSUES\nAT STATE MEETING\nBoyce Tells Maryland Finan\nciers Both Systems Have\nBrilliant Futures.\nBRANCHES BEST IN CITY,\nGROUP IDEA IN COUNTRY\nAssociation Also Urged to Seek\nMuch Closer Harmony With\nFanning Interests.\nBY EDWARD C. STONE.\nBranch and group banking loomed\nlarge In the discussion at the annual\nconvention of the Maryland Bankers\u2019\nAssociation. Heyward E. Boyce of Bal\ntimore. one of the leading bankers in\nthe State, declared that both branch\nbanking and group banking have a great\nfuture. So far, however, branches in\ncommunities far away from the home\noffice have not proved profitable or\npracticable.\n\"A bank is an indissoluable part of\nthe community,\u201d he said, \u201cand its\nsuccessful operations depends upon its\nknowledge of local conditions.\u201d For that\nreason he sees branch banks which are\na long distance from the home offices\nfacing a problem very difficult to over\ncome. In his opinion the success of\nbranch banks lies largely in the big 1\ncities in which the parent banks are\nlocated.\nMr. Boyce added, however, that the\ngiuup banks are working to overcome\nthis obstacle and in the future, he be\nlieves, this type of banking will be car\nried on successfully. Branch banking,\ngroup banking and unit banking came\nin for their full share of attention, ail\nhaving most ardent advocates. That the\nnext 25 years will see evolution, almost\nrevolution, in present banking methods,\nwas the general conclusion reached.\nMr. Boyce turned from his remarks on\nbanking systems long enougn to de\nclare that he believes the Nation is re\ngaining its stride in business and that\nprosperity is indicated by banking\nfigures. \u201cMore money is now being de\nposited in banks,\" he said, \u201cand pecple\n\u2022re seeking fewer loans because of their\ntimidity since the depression.\u201d He pre\ndicted an early return to normal busi\nness.\nHarmony With Farmer Urged.\n\"Big business and banks are usually\nassociated together,\u201d Judge Frank 1\nDuncan of Towson, Md., declared at the\nsame convention, at Atlantic City, \u201cbut\nfor the future of the Nation and the\nbanking business we must seek har\nmony with the farmer. A great volume\nof the Nation\u2019s business is done di\nrectly and indirectly through the agri\nculturists.\u201d\nDuncan said the agricultural\nc\u2014 had confined its work largely\nto the youth of Maryland and that it\nhad sought to instill a renewed' interest\nin agriculture by teaching the boys\nmodem and scientific methods of farm\ning.\nThe legislative committee, through its\nchairman, Webster Bell of Baltimore,\nreported that a bill would be presented\nto the next session of the Legislature\nto legalize bank transactions on Sat\nurday afternoon and that the bill would\ncontain a clause which would not make\nit necessary for banks which usually\nclose Saturday afternoons to remain\nopen.\nAnother bill which the committee will\npropose is one to reduce bank taxes\nthrough a change in the present sys\ntem of taxation as it applies to banks.\nAt present Maryland taxes a bank's\nstock, net earnings and assets. The\ncommittee proposes that the State tax\ncmlv the bank\u2019s stock values.\na third message sponsored by the\ni committee aims to obtain a higher in\nterest rate than 6 per cent on demand i\nloans in excess of $5,000.\nNew Chapin-Sacks President.\nAt a meeting of the board of directors\nof Chapin-Sacks Corporation at the lo\ncal offices Friday afternoon, the resig\nnation of E. S. Perot, jr., was accepted\nand E. J, Mather of New York was\nelected president in his place. Mr.\nPerot has been made chairman of the\nboard of directors of Southern Dairies,\nwith which Chapin-Sacks is closely af\nfiliated.\nE. J. Mather is one of the leading\u2019of\nficials in National Dairy Products which\nnow controls Chapin-Sacks and South\nern Dairies. Several months ago Xraft\nCheese secured control of Southern\nDairies. Later National Dairy Products,\nwhich has been pushing an expansion\nplan with great rapidity, secured con\ntrol of Kraft Cheese.\nBy this move National Dairy Prod\nucts came into control of Southern\nDairies and also of Chapin-Sacks. The\nFame corporation also controls the\nChestnut Farms Dairy Corporation of\nthis city as one of its many units.\nChapin-Sacks, under the leadership\nof E. S. Perot, has made an unusually\ngood showing in expanding the business\nand increasing earnings.\nD. C. Convention Call Sent Out.\nChairman George O. Vass announced\nyesterday that the publicity committee\nhad sent out the third announcement\nregarding the District Bankers\u2019 Asso\nciation convention to be held at Ashe\nville. N. C.. June 5 to 8.\nThis \u201ccall,\u201d as it is termed, contains\na vast amount of detailed information\nfor the delegates and friends regarding\ndining car arrangements, shipment of\ntrunks, etc., of interest only to those\nwho are to make the \u201cSkyland\" visit.\nIncidentally, Chairman Vass reported\nthat reservations so far received by the\ntransportation committee have exceeded\nthose received on all previous years on\nthe same drte. This bears out the ex\npectation already voiced that the at\ntendance will make a new\u2019 record.\nFinancial Giants May Be Queens.\n\"Do not minimize the importance of\nwomen in modern fiance,\u201d Thomas\nTemple Hoyne, Chicago economist,\nwarned the representatives of the Asso\nciated Stock Exchanges, in an address\nat their fourth annual convention at\nMinneapolis. \u201cThe great money poten\ntates of the future may not be kings,\nbut queens.\n\"In 1926. women making individual\nreturns paid taxes on $3,297,527,098;\nindividual men. including those report\ning as heads of a family, paid taxes on\n$4,741,136,177, a ratio of approximately\n41 per cent to 57 per cent. Women com\npose the majority of stockholders in\nmany great companies. They make tip\nmore than 50 per cent of the 419,000\nstockholders of the American Telephone\nTelegraph Co., the largest and\nwealthiest corporation lr. the world.\nThey are beneficiaries in 30 per cent of\nthe $100,000,000,000 of life insurance\npolicies in force nr the United States,\nare inheriting 70 per .ent of the es\ntates left by men and 64 per cent of\nthe estates left by women.\n\u201cOne fanciful statistician has calcu\nlated that if women maintain their pres\nent rate of ascendency all the wealth'\ncf this country will be in feminine\nhands by 2025.\"\nEASTERN RAILROAD SITUATION\nALIVE WITH MERGER RUMORS\nPurchase of D., L. W. Stock by New\nYork Central Revives Discussion of\nPossible Realignments of Carriers.\nSpecial Dispatch to The Star.\nNEW YORK, May 24.\u2014Major move\nments in the Eastern railroad sttaution\nare expected to follow close upon the j\npurchase of a sizable block of Dela\nware. Lackawanna ft Western stock in\nbehalf of the New York Central.\nThe 77,225 shares of Lackawanna,\nbought at about $l4O a share, near the\naverage price this year but 15 points\nabove the current quotation, give the\nNew York Central a small interest com\npared with that held by the Baker snd\nVanderbilt families and their friends,\nwhich is believed to be between 400.000\nand 500,000 shares. It is an evident,\nhowever, that the New York Central as\na corporation Is definitely determined\nto strengthen Its position in competi\ntive territory and is preparing to make\na trade with the Baltimore ft Ohio for\nthe Reading common and preferred\nstocks which it holds and which the\nBaltimore ft Ohio should have in order\nto exert full influence in Reading and\nJersey Central affairs.\nMay Extend Holdings.\nFor years the New York Central and\nthe Baltimore ft Ohio each held 25 per\ncent of Reading common and preferred\nstocks. Some months ago the Baltimore\nOhio increased its ownership, by open\nmarket operations and purchases\nthrough private negotiations, to 34 per\ncent. It was understood that interests\nfriendlv to the road have sufficient\nstock to extend the Baltimore ft Ohio\ninfluence to ever 45 per cent of Reading\nshares.\nThe New York Central has never\nbeen willing to agree to trade out of\nReading until It had retained an in\nterest in either the Lehigh Valley or the\nLackawanna, and so strengthen its posi\ntion in traffic affairs in New York and\nINVESTMENT BOND\nSITUATION IS QUIET\nFlotation of New Securities\nDuring Week Has Greatly j\nIncreased Supply.\nSpecial Dispatch to The Btar.\nNEW YORK. May 24.\u2014This has been\nanother week of large issues of new\nsecurities, and of limited changes in\nthe prices of bonds. Supply has ex- j\nceeded demand, so the situation\nwith respect to undigested bonds is not\nimproving. On the other hand, there\nhas been a slightly better tone to high- I\ngrade issues and a continuation of the\ninstitutional and corporation inquiry j\nfor all classes of short-term Issues of\ngood quality.\nSome of the outstanding loans of the\nweek have been the $30,000,000 B. F.\nGoodrich Co. 6 per cent convertible\ndebentures; $30,000,000 Province of\nOntario 4 is; $17,500,000 American\nSmelting ft Refining 6 jper cent second\npreferred stock; $10,000,000 Southern\nNew England Telephone 5 per cent de\nbentures; $11,500,000 Southern Natural\nGas Corporation 6 per cent convertibles\nand 150.000,000 of National Power ft\nLight 6 per cent preferred stock.\nAmong the smaller offerings have\nbeen $6 000,000 of the Glidden Co. 5-\nyear s*/2 per cent notes, $4,050,000 of\nGeneral American Tank Car 4Vs per\ncent equipment trust certificates and\n$3,000,000 General Bronze 10 per cent\nconvertibles. It is rather significant j\nthat so large a proportion of the week\u2019s\nnew offerings were of a non-convertible\ntype. This is in line with the high\nproportion of strictly fixed interest\nobligations during the year.\nMoney Rates.\nEasier money rates, as represented In\nthe open market for call loan*, in time\nloans and in bankers\u2019 bills, have had\nno appreciable effect on bond prices.\nThe only improvement in the situation,\nso far as long-term bonds are con- j\ncerned, has been in the trend to a little\nwider spread In maturities as the very\nshort notes have been absorbed, com\npelling buyers to accept one-year notes\nwhere they had been taking six-month\nnotes and two-year notes in the place\nof one-year notes. It is expected that\ngradually this will extend the field of i\ndemand Into longer maturities.\nThe chief interest at the moment!\ncenters in the new German reparations\nloan, whose terms are expected to be j\ndefinitely known next week. There has\nbeen more discussion and controversy\nover this issue than any other, domestic\nor foreign, in months. Not only has\nthere been a striking difference of\nopinion as to the price and yield be\ntween American and foreign bankers,\nbut also among those in this country\nwho will be called upon to distribute\nthe American portion of the loan. It\nseems to be accepted that the coupon\nrate will be 5Vs per cent, or the same\nas on the $50,000,000 Japanese gov\nernment bonds offered two weeks ago\nat 90 and selling this week at nearly a\n2-point premium.\nLoan Likely to \u201cGo Over.\u201d\nThose who feel that the German loan\nshould be offered on at least a 6 per\ncent basis, base their conclusions on the\nreturn available not only on the Ger-1\nman government 7s, but on th<\u2019 large j\nnumber of other Gentian issues in which I\nthe German government has in Interest\nand whose yield runs well above 6 per\ncent.\nThere is no doubt that tne loan will\n\u2018go over\u201d so far as the syndicate is\nconcerned. They would not permit it\nto show the slightest evidence of failing.\nJust how far It will find Its way into j\nthe hands of the ultimate consumers\nand be taken in small average lots Is\nnot so certain and will depend entirely\non whether it gives a good yield or one j\nof only moderate t ize.\nOUTLOOK FOR MOTION\nPICTURES OPTIMISTIC\nPatronage of motion pictures during j\nthe first three months of 1930 gave the j\nappearance of being depression-proof\nRecent reports, however, indicate that\nat last the effect of the sustained de\npression is being felt by the motion pic\nture theaters in many sections of the\ncountry, according to a current surveyj\nof the Standard Statistics Co. of New j\nYork. This survey continues, in part;\n\"Two factors may easily cause exag\ngerated reports of decreased attend\nance. The first is the normal seasonal\ndecrease occasioned by the general\ntendency at this time of the year for\nall people to seek recreation in the open\nair The second is that this month\nopens the trading season between the\nproducers and exhibitors for the book\ning of pictures to be shown during the\ncoming fiscal year, and the exhibitor's\ntendency is, for trading purposes, to\npresent his current position and out\nlook In the very worst light.\u201d\nFINANCIAL AND CLASSIFIED\nShe jlumlaii Star\nWASHINGTON, D. C\u201e SUNDAY MORNING. MAY 23. U):iQ.\nPennsylvania. It once held a large\nblock of Lehigh Valley, but sold it to\nL. F. Lcree. who later disposed of it to\nthe Pennsylvania Railroad under the\narrangement described Friday by Presi\ndent W. W. Atterbury in the hearing\nbefore the Interstate Commerce Com\nmission.\nInasmuch as the Van Sweringen in\nterests are most friendly to the New\nYork Central, it is not believed there\nwill be any strong objection on their\npart to giving up the Lackawanna, al\nthough In the Interstate Commerce\nCommission's consolidation plan this\nroad was allocated to the Nickel Plate,\nin spite of the fact that it already held\ncontrol of the Erie.\nJust what the attitude of the Penn\nsylvania Railroad will be, however, to\nward complete control of the Reading\nby the Baltimore ft Ohio remains to be\nseen. From time to time there have\nbeen indications that the Pennsylvania\nwould oppose such an arrangement, on\nthe basis that it tvould rob it of a large\namount of traffic which it interchanges\nwith the Reading.\nOpposition to Transfer.\nStrong opposition to the transfer of\nReading to the Baltimore ft Ohio has\ncome from Philadelphia interests. How\never, the Interstate Commerce Commis\nsion has gone on record, not only in its\nofficial plan, but on other occasions, as\nfavoring the control and management\nof the Reading by the Willard road.\nEventually this application is expected\nto be granted. It- now seems nearer\nconsummation than ever, with the New\nYork Central definitely preparing to\nbalance Its loss in Reading holdings\nthrough a gain in those of Lackawanna.\n(CoDvriEht, 1930.1\nANSWER IN STEEf\nMERGER SUIT FILED\nBethlehem Company Denies\nAny Attempt to Force Unior.\nWith Competitor.\nBy the Associated Press.\nYOUNGSTOWN, Ohio, May 24\nBethlehem Steel Corporation and I\nYoungstown Sheet Tube Co., today\nfiled separate answers in Common Pleas\nCourt here to a suit seeking to enjoin\nI the merger of the two companies. The\nanswers were filed only a few minutes\nbefore the legal time limit expired,\ni Bethlehem admitted that merger nego\ntiations began in January and February\nthis year, with James A. Campbell and\nH. G. Dalton negotiating with Eugene\nGrace, Bethlehem president. Campbell\nis chairman of Sheet ft Tube; Dalton\nIs a director of both Sheet and Tube\nand Bethlehem, and a partner in Pick\nands, Mather ft Co., Or? firm which\nhe contracts with both companies.\nCampbell and Dalton \"exercised their\nown independent judgment.\u201d Bethle\nhem's answer said, adding that Dalton s\nfinancial interest in Sheet <fc Tube\ngreatly exceeded his interest In Beth\nlehem.\"\nBethlehem denied that its record for\nearnings has been irregular or that J\nBethlehem common is regarded as\n\"highly speculative.\u201d The company said\nthe employment of Price, Waterhouse I\nft Co. as auditors was not suggested by\nBethlehem.\nThe final basis of exchange, one and\none-third shares of Bethlehem for one\nof Sheet it Tube, was more favorable to\nSheet St Tube than the basis suggested\nby the auditors, Bethlehem said.\nINCREASE IN GRAIN\nPRICES LOOKED FOR!\nFarmers Hope Gain in Demand;\nWill Bring About Better\nMarket.\n_____\nSpecial Dispatch to The Star.\nKANSAS CITY, Mo., May 24.\u2014Nod\nding heads of wheat as far North as\nNebraska indicate the near approach of\nharvest. Experts draw various conclu\nsions as to the early maturity of the\nplant, and complaints that the stand\nis far less encouraging than was indl-1\ncated earlier are common. But there j\nwill be a fairly generous crop, and its j\nultimate output may improve in the\nnext month\u2014or, of course, what hap\npened last year, a sudden deterioration,\nmav eventuate.\nIn the meanwhile, the producer Is'\nmerely waiting, and the grain farmer\nhas been joined by the live stock raiser\nin being affected by the low price level\nof products. The sliding downward of j\nI the live stock market has brought some\ndiscouragement to those interested, but\na considerable portion of the feeders\nhad been sold before the recent depres\nsion in the market.\nIt is felt that if the agricultural\nI country can get through the next 60\nj days, by which time the income from\nthe grain marketing will be felt, there\nI should be an easier money market and\nimprovement in trade. The .first of Au\ngust is tentatively set for betterment,\nwith the expectation that by that time\nwhatever benefit is to come from con\ngressional action will be felt and possi-\nI bly some improvement in the price lev\nels of production from foreign demand\nARUNDEL CORPORATION.\nBALTIMORE. May 24 (Special).\u2014\nContinuing its steady earning gains over\nj each corresponding month of last year,\nthe Arundel Corporation reports net\ni profit for the month of April amounting\nto $234,308.\nThis represents a gain of $111,069\nI ever April a year ago, when net earn\nings were only $123,239.\nAfter all deductions. Including depre\nciation, Federal income tax and other\ndeductions, earnings for the first four\nmonths of 1930 amounted to $629,822,\nagainst $444,405 for the same period last\nyear, a gain of $185,417.\nThe balance sheet at the end of the\nmonth Showed current assets of $5,158,-\n003, against current liabilities of $775,-\n981, a ratio of approximately 6'i to 1.\nOil and Gas Land Deal.\nCHARLESTON, W. Va., May 24 (A*).\u2014\nPurchase of 16,000 acres of oil and gae\nproperty in Northern West Virginia and\nSouthwestern Pennsylvania by the Mid\nland Natural Gas Co. for $2,000,000\nwas announced here today by John\nEgghan Kelly, New York, vice president\nof the company. The announcement\nsaid there were 175 oil and gas wells\nlocated in the \u00bbc\u00abage\nSTOCKS MARK TIME\nPENDING EXPECTED\nUPSWING IN TRADE\nDefinite Trend Lacking Dur\ning Week\u2019s Dealings in\nEquities Market.\nLOW MONEY RATES FAIL\nTO AID BUSINESS WORLD\nEffects of Overproduction Are Still\nApparent, With Commodity\nPrices Weak.\nBY CHARLES F. SPEARE.\nSpecial Dispatch to The Star.\nNEW YORK. May 24.\u2014This week\u2019s\nmarkets in \u201cequities\" and fixed interest\nobligations have developed no trend.\nSurfeited with money at steadily de\nclining rates. Wall Street studies price\nlists but hesitates to buy. It is wait\ning for some evidence of permanently\nimproved business before venturing\nagain into speculative fields.\nMeanwhile it keeps away from those\nshares into which the mild epidemic of\ndividend reductions may spread. Trans\nactions on the Stock Exchange have\ndeclined to the smallest totals since\nJanuary. Those that are recorded\nmainly represent the day to day whims\nof the professionals.\nLowest interest rates have so far been\nas little stimulating to trade as to\nsecurities. The effect of reduced dis\ncount rates over the country has grad\nually brought about concessions to\ncommercial borrowers that would justify\nthe making of new loans if good busi\nness prospects were in sight. The evils\nof overproduction by producers of raw\nmaterials and of manufactured goods\nand also of construction companies and\nthe overindulgence of the public in\nluxuries are yet to be corrected. At the\nbeginning of a season when the mo\nmentum of trade slows down there is\nless prospect than normally for an\n.expansion in corporation earnings.\nCommodities Slip Again.\nFrom time to time in the last two\nmonths there have been indications\nthat the downward trend of commodity\nprices had culminated. The turn\nseemed at hand in April, when there\nwas a slight rally from the progressive\ndecrease that had covered a period of\nabout nine months. However, a new\nlow average was reached this week, with\nthe advance in metals overbalanced by\na series of declines in prices for iron\nand steel, dairy products and rubber. I\nThe situation in this country is par\nalleled abroad, where commodities are\nquoted at a new low average in Great\nBritain, France. Germany and Italy.\nFortunately grain prices appear to be\nnearer the point of stabilization, since\nwhat was considered an official \u201cpeg\"\nwas placed against the price of wheat.\nThe record of decreasing commercial\nloans indicates the degree of deflation\nthat has been taking place following the\nstock panic of last November. Such\nloans have been reduced $1,300,000,000.\nor in larger percentages than at any\ntime since business stagnation gripped\nthe country in 1921. This is statistical\nevidence of a subnormal condition in\nbusiness of which poor earnings and\nreduced dividends are a natural phase.\nRail Consolidation.\nThe country is going through the\nstage of starvation that frequently fol\ni lows a period of excess, but which will 1\nI place it in a much healthier condition\ni after a few months and permit it to put\non fat rapidly once the turn comes.\nIt has been apparent this week that\nnot much can be expected in the way of\nrailroad consolidation along the lines\nmapped out by the Interstate Commerce\nCommission. Not only is there objec-1\ntion to this from the carriers themselves,\nbut in political circles and by labor\ngroups. There will be movements to\nward centralized control, such as those\nrecently completed by the Van Swerln\ngens in securing a hold of the Missouri\nPacific, by the Baltimore Ohio in\nI creating a new route to Chicago through\npurchase of the Buffalo. Rochester\nPittsburgh, and the Buffalo Susque\nhanna. and in the New York Central\u2019s\nInvestment just made in the Delaware,\nLackawanna Western.\nOne of the tenets of the \"new era\u201d\ndoctrine has been that railroad stocks\nshould be exchanged for public utilities.\nBefore a corporation or an individual\ndecides on such a policy it might be well\nto study some of the causes that brought\nabout opposition to the railroads, and\nalso to read from the history of the\ngreat industrial trusts of 30 years ago\ntheir experience with hostile legislation.\nThe public utility companies have\nbeen shrewd in extending their owner\nship into the field of their consumers.\nAs an investment, their preferred stocks,\nI in which consumers have made their\nchief purchases, have been second to\nnone of their class. The movement has\nhad a wide scope on the Pacific Coast\nand in the Eastern Atlantic States. In\nspite of it there are very pronounced in\ndications that in three of these States\npublic utility regulation will be an active\npolitical slogan in this Autumn's cam\npaign.\nSo far as there is any visible public\nobjection to railroad consolidation\u2014and\nthere is not much more of this than\nthere is of favor for mergers\u2014it arises\nout of the fear that too much power will\nbe placed in the hands of small groups\nof men and corporations and that pres\nent local advantages will be lost through\na centralized absentee control.\n(Copyright, 1930.1\nCANADA SEES TRADE\nPICK-UP IN AUGUST\nExport Improvement and Good\nCrops Vital Factors in Better\nConditions.\nSpecial Dispatch to The Star.\nTORONTO, May 24 Like the United\nStates, Canada does not foresee any\ngreat improvement in business before\nthe middle of August. In the first place,\neverything depends upon an improve\ni ment in the Dominion's export trade,\nupon good crops and upon some remark\nable strikes in the mineral areas, where\nso much money is at present expended\nin exploration. And. secondly, Canada\u2019s\nreturn of prosperity will be delayed\nuntil greater business activity returns\nto the United States.\nAt present the second quarter seems\nlikely to show greater prosperity than\nthe first three months in certain lines.\nFor instance, retail trade shows greater\nactivity in the warmer weather, al\nthough wholesale buying is marked by\nthe same cautiousness that has charac\nterized such business since the begin\nning of the year.\nThe warmer weather in the West\nduring the present week and the heavy,\nalthough scattered rains, he.\"e helped\ni the crops in many prairie districts.\nBusiness News\nin\nRetrospect\nSome Washington Securi\nties Have Shown Signs\nof Weakness, Due to\nShrinkage in the Earn\ning Power of the Com\npanies Involved.\nBY I. A. FLEMING.\nWashington securities, which re\nsponded but moderately to the big price\ndecline on Wall Street last Fall, are be\nginning to shiver in a manner to dis\ncourage their holders.\nThe Senate of the United States is\nopposed to a merger of the street rail\nways of the District, at least at this\ntime, and with adjournment but a few\ndays away there can be no hope for\nthe measure at this time.\nSo far as the street railways are con\ncerned this should not affect Washing\nton Railway Electric Co., as the pre\nferred shares are assured of their 5\nper cent distribution annually, while\nthe common, with the last reported sale\nat 550, Is closely held by the North\nAmerican Co.\nShareholders In the Capital Traction\nCo. have about given up hope of being\nable to obtain consideration from Con\ngress or the Public Utilities Commission\nand are hoping that the courts will\ncome to the aid of the carrier. The\ndirectors have gone about as far as they\ncan on the tapping of their surplus to\nhelp pay dividends.\nFor many months earnings have been\nshowing more or less severe losses.\nMarch figures have just been given out,\nwith a loss of $26,000, the net being\nbut $45,630.\nAny change for the month of April\nwould be a miracle \u2014nothingllessor\nthere are several cab companies now\ndoing business on the basis of 35 cents\n\u201canywhere in the city proper.\u201d\nAgreement Seems Reasonable.\nAn agreement in Congre-s for the\ncontrol of the taxicab companies by the\nUtilities Commission and for a service\ncharge fair to all carriers has been sug\ngested and would be fair to the street\ncar properties.\nCapital Traction stock is still owned\nvery largely in this city, by Washing\nton people, who for many years have\nfound it a splendid investment, but the\nintensive competition of low-priced used\ncars, down to $25, carrying several\nworkers to and from their jobs, and the\nhigher-priced car competition has cut\ntheir earnings under dividend require\nments at present rate.\nThere is no longer any question but\nwhat a cycle of business depression is\nhaving its effect all over the country.\nApril earnings of corporations continue\nto show impressive losses, dividends are\nbeing cut, while financing plans con\ntinue to provide for many new Issues\nof securities.\nMergenthaler has not cut its regular\ndividend, nor is there any probabilities\nthat It will, but It has taken the pre\ncaution to clip off the 25 cents a share\nextra which It has been paying for some\nmonths.\nThe directors and officers probably\nfeel that any corporation with a clean\nslate, without bonds, debts to banks or\nplasters on new> property, and. in addi\ntion, over a million dollars In cash. Is\ndoing well enough when it pays 6 per\ncent sans the extra.\nIt is a fact that the bankers of\nWashington would be glad to keep\ntheir funds employed these days at 6\nper cent. So close is the margin of\nprofit that many banks will find it hard\nto earn Interest rates.\nIt la Hard to Believe.\nThere Is not a banker In this city\nwho would have believed it possible if\nCol. Robert Newton Harper had not,\nover his own signature, admitted that\nhe had actually sold the control, most\nof his stock, In his pet, the District\nNational Bank, sired, nursed through\nUs swaddling age, its policies fought\nj for with bank examiners, housed and\nj the housing enlarged\u2014all by Col. R. N.\nj Harper\u2014until it reached the age of\nmanhood, then watched over closer than\never to its great success.\nOne month is the longest time that\nCol. Harper has vacationed in the 52\nyears of his busy life and it is much\nmore than probable that he was busy\nwith bank affairs half of that time or\nelse had some public project in the in\nterest of the people on his mind, look\ning after the installation of a President\nof the United States, building an audi\ntorium. a triumphal arch for our sol\ndiers to parade under or some other of\nhis numerous efforts for Washington.\nHe never failed.\nFrequently in the past few years there\nhave been rumors of a merger between\nthe District and the Commercial Banks.\nThose acquainted with conditions did\nnot believe a merger possible so long as\nCol. Harper and R. Golden Donaldson\nremained at the heads of their respec\ntive banks.\nThey are both out now r and one never\nknows what may happen in times like\nthese\nNothing that Col. Harper could do\nwould create greater surprise than his\naction in selling out. It certainly re\nquired plenty of money to pay for the\nstock the colonel has or will turn over\nto Mr. Evans and his associates.\nCol. Harper retires with the warm\nfriendship of the banking fraternity.\nHis directors are very loyal to him. if\nhe really does take a rest, much needed\nand which he promises himself, he will\nhave the kindest thoughts and best\nwishes of his friends\u2014but this is an\nother point on which these self-same\nfriends are skeptical.\nAs to Small Loans.\nThe United States Senate actually\nconsidered the question of enacting\nlegislation that would put the Treas\nury in the small loan business. How\never, there were those wise enough to\nkill the proposition.\nCongress has forced the pawnbroker\nand his per cent per month out of the\ncorporate limits of the city. Small loans\nwithout security is but an opportunity\nfor trouble. Character loans may be\nobtained at many of the banks through\nthe establishment of an acquaintance\nproperly introduced and your references\npresented.\nUnsecured loans depend on the ability\nof the maker of such instruments to\nmeet at maturity; the willingness to\nliquidate promptly. Small loans as a\nrule depend on continued employment\nand non-interference with wages.\nIt is a fact that one can make small\nloans, if half w r ay decent, easily enough.\nBut every day victims of this method\nare paying pawn broker rates of in\nterest.\nIf you want SSOO you may borrow it,\nif you have a good reputation and job,\nby agreeing to pay these charges. First,\n6 per cent per annum on the entire\namount for one year, interest payable\nin advance and deducted from the prin\ncipal before payment Is made, plus $lO\nfor investigation, plus an indefinite sum\nfor your insurance policy to insure pay\nment of the loan. Advance charges\namount to about $45 on a SSOO policy.\nMidway in the life of the note the\nmaker, if he lives up to his agreement,\nhas returned half of the net sum loaned,\nbut he receives no rebate for the in\nterest on the first $250 taken out at the\ntime of signing. Likewise there is no\nadjustment of interest as the payments\ncro made cn- the second half.\nFOREIGN BUSINESS\nAWAITS ADVENT OF\nREPARATIONS LOAN\nConditions in Britain and on\nContinent Described as\nQuiet in Review.\nUSUAL SPRING REVIVAL\nFAILS TO MATERIALIZE\nPurchasing Power Still Impaired\nAfter Collapse in Stock\nMarkets.\nSpecial Dispatch to The Star.\nNEW YORK. May 24\u2014Cable dis\npatches to The Business Week give the\nfollowing survey of business abroad for\nthe week ending May 24:\nEurope.\u2014Noth withstanding the ex\ntraordinary amount of capital mobilized\npreparatory to the offering of Inter\nnational Bank shares and Young bonds,\nmoney remains ample at the lowest\nrates since the war. This plethora of\ni idle funds itself Is an index of the de\ngree of business lassitude which exists\nand the new lower price ratios. On the\nother hand, it is in itself a condition\nfacilitating revival. There is no lack of\nadverse criticism of the flotation of\nthe Young bond issue under prevailing\nconditions. J. M. Keynes stigmatizes\nthe issue as one of the stupidest con\nceivable undertakings. The condemna\ntion is not unjustified, comments the\nGerman Volkswirt, \"since the world\u2019s\nmoney markets for months are dislo\ncated In order to prepare for the flota\ntion of an issue without economic oc\ncasion. The purpose belongs to a chap\nter of post-war economics idiocy for\npolitical motives.\u201d\nProspects for Loan.\nNevertheless, now that financial\npreparations have been made and only\ntechnical difficulties protract final ar\nrangements, business only wants to get\nthe issue out of the way. from capital\nmarkets. Oversubscription by France\nis considered assured and no material\ndifficulty Is anticipated in marketing\nthe other European quotas, but response\nin the United Stated is queried. Whereas\nat the time of the Paris conference\nparticipation of the United States was\nconsidered an indispensable backbone,\nit is now pointed out that the whole\nissue could be readily placed in Europe\nwere the French desire to make the\nUnited States a joint stockholder in her\nreparations claims disregarded, and\nFrench readiness to subscribe accepted.\nFailure of business to realize the\nusual degree of Spring revival has\ndampened optimism. Realization is\npenetrating that no rapid recovery is\nprobable. Instead a protracted period\nof restricted production and trade is\nin prospect until world purchasing\npower gradually recovers the losses suf- j\nsered through the collapse of the price\nceiling. Recurrent relapses of pessi\nmism. however, exaggerate the difflcul\nties. It is anticipated that the Summer\nseason will be marked by a high degree i\nof financial activity stimulating busi- j\nness initiative and gradual expansion\nof turnover.\nIron and steel conditions are reported\nunsatisfactory throughout Europe, ex\ncept in France, where the domestic\nmarket is relatively strong. Except In\nFrance, present production quotas ex\nceed market demands. The steel cartel\nis internally strained by the desire, par\nticularly among the Germans, to re\nduce quotas *25 per cent, which would\nfurther tend to create a production\ndeflet in France and allow for greater\nimports. The French, naturally, are op\nposed to allowing less favorable condi\ntions in Germany and elsewhere to\noperate toward restriction of their pro\nduction below home sales possibilities.\nGreat Britain.\u2014lt Is not impossible\nthat business will take heart, once the\nYoung bond issue is out of the way and\nfinancial markets are again normalized,\nbut for the moment sentiment is dis\ntinctly gloomy. During the weri: Lon\ndon lost another 20 millions in gold\nto Paris. Because London\u2019s key posi\ntion as a financial center is founded\nupon the solidarity of sterling exchange,\nsuch losses always exercise a dispro\nportionately depressing psychological\neffect. They are now accentuated, be\ncause no further large African or Aus\ntralian arrivals of gold, such as offset\nrecent losses, are scheduled. Foreign\ntrade returns add gloom, with April\nthe worst month since the 1926 strike\nyear.\nIndustrial reports emphasize the\nhand-to-mouth character of buying,\nrestricted continental demand and ex\ncessively sharp competition over what\nbusiness is available. Several individ\nual woolen mills have compromised on\nwage disputes and resumed activity.\nConditions Quiet in France.\nFrance. \u2014Business is featureless and\ntranquil. The stock market is marking\ntime. Interest is absorbed in the In\nternational Bank and Young bond is\nsues. Threefold oversubscription of the\nFrench quota of $80,000,000 to $90,000,-\n000 is expected. Progressive liquidation\nof foreign obligations, utilizing a share\nof the Young bond proceeds and large\ntreasury and sinking fund surpluses, are\nexpected during the year. This will re\nduce capital congestion.\nThe most recent production index\nfor the end of March was 144. com\npared with the 1929 average of 139.\nBuilding and iron and steel are each\nup 2 points; automobiles. 15. Foreign\ntrade for the first four months shows\nimports down 8 per cent by value, but\nup 2,400.000 tons by weight, notably in\nraw materials, an index of manufac\nturing activity. Exports are slightly\nlower, both in value and weight. The\nrailroads plan to ask for a 20 per cent\nincrease in passenger and a 6 per cent\nincrease in freight rates, due to unsat\nisfactory results of operations last year.\nAs a consequence of the recent increase\nin automobile tariffs, the local General\nMotors dismissed 76 employes and dis\ncontinued advertising. Other dealers\nare similarly economizing in overhead.\nThe situation for the American auto\nmotive trade is worse than was at first\nanticipated. The position of the Ford\nassembly plant, however, is relatively\nfavorable because it imported heavy\nstocks of parts prior to the tariff in\ncrease. and now is negotiating with\nFrench steel w\u2019orks for future require\nments. thus minimizing imports.\nHolland.\u2014Business is generally dull,\nwith money again very easy and\nthe stock exchange lifeless. The deep\nening depression in Germany is viewed\nwith uneasiness; likewise the favorable\nreception of Young bonds is not as\nsured, since, unless there is a higher\nyield than is so far indicated they are\nof little interest to the Investor.\nTwentschebank, Holland's third largest,\nwith 11 branches, has merged six pro\nvincial banks with 40 branches, thus\nmarking another step in banking con\ncentration.\nGermany. Although the stronger\ntone on the stock market is sustained,\ncurrent business Indicators still fall to\nshow improvement. The feebleness of\nClassified Ads\nPages 5 to 12\nHouses Delegates j\njn H&i\nHL vJhlJUBfr\nLUTHER E. SCHREINER,\nChairman of the hotel committee of the\nDistrict Bankers\u2019 Association, Is one of\nWashington's busiest bankers just now.\nHe is arranging accommodation for the\nAsheville convention, which takes place\nJune 8 to t.\nCouzens Measure\nIs Seen as Blow\nTo Carrier Rates\nRailroad Economists De\nclare Bill Would Seriously\nAffect Present Structure.\nBY J. C. BOYLE.\nWho pays the freight? Whoever does\nis deeply concerned in the measure\nwhich is known as the Couzens resolu\ntion and which has been passed by the\nSenate. This measure would take away\nfrom the Interstate Commerce Com\nmission the right to approve railroad\nconsolidations pending new legislation.\nRairoad economists who have studied\nthe situation declare that this legis\nlative mea'ure not only affects pending\nconsolidations, but the entire rate j\nstructure of the country. If this meas- j\nure is pas-ed. they assert, it will in\nvalidate every rate problem regarded I\nas solved up to this time.\nThe result, they say. will be the\nmaking of a factory delivery price and\na consequent refusal of producers to'\n1 make a delivered price. The slowing\ndown on retail trade seems obvious\nat least the factory producers count\non it.\nHines\u2019 Analysis.\nj The carriers occupy a unique posi- J\nJ tion. They are common carriers and\nl they have in some instances a monop- j\noly. Whether they needed competition\ni was a question that lay with the In-\nI terstate Commerce Commission. The\ncarrier? have obeyed the law and have i\nset fr?ight and passenger rates accord-\ningly. but now, if the old operations of i\nthe Interstate Commission are ques- j\ntinned, the cost of transportation is in\nquestion.\nWalker D. Hines, one of the out\nstanding authorities in the field of 1\npublic utilities, analyzes the situation\nas follows:\n1. The Couzens resolution throws the\nrailroads back on the unrelieved prohi- J\nbitions of the anti-trust laws, with re\nsulting uncertainty.\n2. It establishes the principle of direct\ncongressional interference with the:\ncommission's statutory discretion, with i\ninevitable Impairment of the commis- j\nsion's morale.\n3. The \u201cholding company\u201d provision j\nseems to go even to the length of\nrendering unlawful the continued exer\ncise of a rail carrier's control if its\nsubsidiaries, where that control was\nacquired prior to the transportation act\nand therefore without authority from\nthe commission.\n\"The resolution suspends until March\n4, 1931, with strong prospects of long\nextensions thereafter if the resolution is\nonce adopted.\u201d Mr. Hines said, the\npowers of the Interstate Commerce\nCommission over the acquisition of rail\nroads or railroad control and over rail\nroad consolidations in all cases where\nany such step would involve eny viola\ntion of the anti-trust laws as they\nexisted prior to the transportation act.\nCommission Orders.\n\u201cSince 1920. the commission has made\norders authorizing acquisitions of rail\nroads or for railroad control affecting\nabout 82.000 miles of railroad, which\nwould have been impracticable as to\nthe bulk of this mileage under the anti\ntrust laws because of involving the\nelimination of some substantial compe\ntition, and much of the remainder\nwould have been uncertain because of\nthe well known uncertainty as to l ow\nthe courts would apply the anti-trust\nlaws to doubtful cases.\n\u201cA very grave feature of this matter\nis the precedent thereby established of\ndirect congressional Interference with\nthe commission\u2019s discretion in the exer\ncise of powers conferred upon it by the\ninterstate commerce act. If this resolu\ntion is passed, it will set the fashion\nfor any disgruntled and more or less\norganized minority to rush to Congress\nto prevent, by Joint resolution, the con\ntinued orderly exercise by the commis\nsion of its statutory functions in other\nrespects. The intimidating effect upon\nthe commission should readily l<e appre\nciated. Even a railroad having no im\nportant concern as to this part of the\nresolution mav find itself seriously em\nbarrassed by the-next attack which may\ncome by virtue of this precedent.\u201d\nCopyright. 1930.1\nContinental\u2019s Interest Abroad.\nNEW YORK. May 24 MPt.\u2014Carl C.\nConway, chairman of the Continental\nCan Co., said, on returning from abroad\ntoday, that his company\u2019s recently ac\nquired interest in the metal box and\nprinting industries In England assured\nContinental of a profitable Investment,\nadding that neither control nor a domi\nnant position in the British canning\nIndustry was being sought.\nagricultural purchasing power and the\nestimated 20 per cent decrease in capi\ntal available for building, compared\nwith the amount that was available last\nyear\u2014equivalent to an employment\ncut of half a million\u2014are the two\nprincipal factors underlying the con\ntraction of industrial activity. April\nexports show a relapse from the March\npeak, though the balance is still f vor\nable. I\nAfter a fortnight's hesitation, the i\nReichsbank followed the recent Inter-\nnational trend in bank rate '-eductions 1\nwith a cut from 5 per cent to 4>j per\ncent. Since private discounts are shad\ning 4 per cent, lowest levels since the i\nwar. the reduction was only a partial i\nrealignment of the bank rate to the\nmarket, and 1s without material busi-\nn?si effect?\nCHAIN STORE HEAD\nPLANS TO LOCALIZE\nALL UNITS IN FIRM\nSaunders Explains Proposal\nto Decentralize Organiza\ntion of 400 Markets.\nSTATE DIRECTORATES\nFEATURE NEW SYSTEM\nSalaries and Purchasing Policy\nWill Be Placed on \u201cAt\nHome\u201d Basis.\nBY JOHN F. SINCLAIR.\nSpecial Dispatch to The Star.\nNEW YORK. May 24.\u2014Clarence\nSaunders o f Memphis, the \u201cstormy\npetrel\u201d of chain store operation, this\nweek assumed full control of the Clar\nence Saunders Stores, Inc., and the\nClarence Saunders Pacific Stores. Inc.,\nwhich operate 400 chain units in 16\nStates, with annual sales of over $40,-\n000,000. He says that every one of theae\nstores will be decentralized\u2014that is, lo\ncally owned, operated and controlled.\nThis is the first important step yet\ntaken to meet chain store opposition in\nthe United States. Here is the way Mr.\nSaunders outlines his new plan:\n\u201cEach State is to have its own board\nof directors. The officers will be se\nlected from the citizenship of that State\nand the banking of all money will be\ndone with the State banks in the com\nmunity where each store operates. All\nwages and salaries will be kept at home.\nThe plans is for each store company to\npurchase every item of merchandise\nposssible from those who operate w'ithln\nthe State in which the store is located.\"\nThe Saunders organization, which\nwill continue as the central buying and\nadvisory body for all the stores, is to re\nceive for its compensation one-half of 1\nper cent on the gross sales from all\nstores.\nThe opposition to chain stores has\ncentralized largely in the small towns\nand villages. A Government survey, al\nready made, however, shows that chain\nstores are developing much more rapid\nly in the great cities than in the rural\nsections.\nThe Saunders announcement Is the\nfirst one issued by an important chain\n|to indicate the growing opposition to\nthat form of organization.\nOne wonders what the reaction of\n\u201cOle Man\u201d Henderson of Station KWKH\nof Shreveport. La., will be to this latest\nevolutionary announcement of his friend\nSaunders.\nSituation in India.\nThe situation in India continues criti\ncal. The British government, watching\nevery move, is extremely anxious over\nthe outcome. Gandhi, in jail, his non\ni rrsVance followers are becoming more\nj rests-ant every day.\nj British India, divided into J 5 admin\nj'fctr.-.tiwrs, each under a governor, has\nfound' the governing problem no sine\n\"crr in recent year*.\nI With total e-ea cf 1 805.000 square\nI r*v!:.. a population cf 318,000,000 peo\nj ole, per cent of whom live on the\nI ond. India is just waking up com\nj mcr c> l!y.\nTiiink of 32 cities in India with a\ni:c;ni-.t:on of more than 100,000 each!\nAnd 51 cities more with a population\njcf frem 30.000 to 100,000!\ni About 8500030,001 a year is raised\n(by trues for the national budget, out of\nI which must be paid the regular British\narmy of GO.OOO men and the native\narmy cf 107.000 men. The total army\nexpenditures for 1928-1929 were $212,-\n000.000.\nThe next 30 days should tell the\nstory.\nTaxicab Rates.\nWith first-hand experience in taxicab\noperations in Chicago, Cleveland, De\ntroit, Pittsburgh. Lcs Angeles, St. Louis\nand Baltimcre. Ernest H. Miller of Chi\ncago, president of the Parmalse Trans\nportation Co., thinks the prevailing\nlate of 25 cents for the first quarter of\na mile and 10 cents for each half mile\nthereafter is a fair, living charge.\nI So the New York rates\u2014ls cents for\nthe first quarter and 5 cents for each\nquarter mile thereafter \u2014Is not a fair,\nliving charge.\nChicago, with its 3,157.000 people, has\n5,200 taxicabs, most of which are owned\nby two companies\u2014the Yellow and the\nChecker. Pittsburgh has 718 cabs, all\nunder Parmalee control. Both of these\ncities have the 25 and 10 cent rate.\nCleveland, with 800,000 people, has\n800 cabs, while New York, with 6,000,-\n000 people, has 20,000 taxicabs.\nMr. Miller contends that both high\nand low\u2019 rates lead to bankruptcy and\nthat the selling of cabs to individual\nowmers cn the installment basis is both\nharmful to the industry and ruinous to\nthe purchasers.\n\u201cGive satisfactory service on a small\nmargin of net return,\u201d said Mr. Miller,\n\u201cand apply the general principles appli\ncable to other public utilities.\u201d\nHow can taxicab service be made\nprofitable, safe, and efficient?\nMr. Miller aifswers\u2014\"Only by a mo\nnoply or semi-monopoly, under super\nvision of some governmental agency,\nwith power to limit the number of cabs,\nby requiring certificates of convenience\nand necessity.\"\n\u201cIn another five years, the taxicabs\nof the United States will all be in the\nhands of two or three big companies.\u201d\nsaid a New York taxicab driver, sadly\nsurveying the field. \u201cThen the individ\nual, owning his own taxi, will have a\nsweet time to break in.\u201d\nMerchadise Mart.\nChicago's Spring contribution to Amer\nican business architecture\u2014the mer\nchandise mart, and its board of trade\n\u2014is an epoch-making one.\nThe merchandise mart, with its 4,000.-\n000 square feet of space, is the largest,\nin the world. Already 82 per cent of its\nspace is taken, with Marshall Field\nCo!, the largest tenants, occupying 20\nacres of floor space.\nWhen the mart was first conceived\nby James Simpson, chairman of Mar\nshall Field <fc Co., it was considered\ntoo ambitious even for Chicago. But\nit starts from scratch a success, be\ncause. as Clyde A. Wells. Its general\nmanager, says, it concentrates under one\nroof the goods of hundreds of manu\nfacturers and wholesalers, \u201cmaking for\nthe great convenience of an army of\nbuyers and resulting in a reduction of\ncost to the retail m r reliant and to the\nultimate consumer.\u201d\n(Copvrinht, 1930. bv North American News\npaper Alliance, i\nSEARS, ROEBUCK SALES.\nCHICAGO. May 24 Sales of\nSears. Roebuck Co. for the fifth\nperiod of its 13-month year totaled\n$30,685,991, compared with $32,698,853\nin the same period. April 24 to May 21,\nof 1829. The decrease was 6.1 per cent.\nIn the five periods ended May 21.\ntotal sales of the mall order-retail\nchain were $140,800,870. against $144,-\n179.104 last year, a 2.3 per cent de\ncrease. The number of retail atores in\noperation was not announced.","height":"25323","width":"19809"}}
